The best hotpot in NYC.  Amazingly fresh and great soup bases.  Pricey but you can't beat the selection and quality here. They redecorate the place every month or so depending on the holiday or season.  They also have delicious and creative ingredients being offered so definitely try those out. Bar none the best hotpot place to try in Brooklyn and NYC.  I prefer a la carte places like these because the quality and freshness is top notch unlike many all you can eat places where you are forced to stuff yourself to get the biggest bang for your buck instead of just enjoying the food itself.  I love the condiments tray at the beginning that's brought to your table so you can make your own sauce. I usually put everything and ask for more of their house sauce.  Dishes I would highly recommend:  - Sliced fatty beef - sliced pork belly - karp fish belly karp (go for the belly since it's boneless and has a great crunch/firmness on the skin. The regular is great too but watch out for the bones) - Mister beef balls - beef short rib - large live sea scallops - cuttlefish paste - large razor clams - fish stomach  As for the soup base definitely the 1/2 Tom Yum and 1/2 Spicy or 1/2 Kim chee  Their service is top notch as well. I recommend to always make a reservation as the place isn't very big and it's quite hard to get a walk in spot during regular dinner hours. They open late (3pm) and close late (2-3am). I prefer the earlier times as the music isn't as loud and it's much brighter unless you like the club atmosphere :)  They also have a Queens location that have little cubbies for holding your phones.

Yes 1 Star. Why? Went there last night with my buddy to enjoy delicious hot pot. This time it has been totally different from our previous times when we used to very much enjoy it. First of all we were never given water, like how is anyone going to enjoy hot pot with no water?? Is this a policy where you ask and shall receive type of thing? That’s bad service. So we only had a small bottle of sake to share with the hot pot. If you are thirsty I would not recommend sipping on the soup base to hydrate, they could have filled our soup up with my stock at least.  Also the policy changed, instead of offering vegetable combo it comes with fish skin. Stupid dried and disgusting fish skin. How are you going to give us fish skin for overly expensive flavors of hot pot. The Tom young spicy soup sucked as well. The meat combo we ordered were also not fresh and not enjoyable. We didn’t even get icecream but we did get gum. And I was such in a rush with disgust, I gave them $100 for $78.00 total and left. Now that I think of it, I gave them too much tip, but we were a bit in shock to realize this mistake and wanted to leave in a rush.  This place currently has found a way to become more expensive while offering so much less. I would not recommend anyone this place in its current state. We miss our past experiences with mister hot pot, but I am now aware of its awfulness that me and my friends will avoid this place as our usual hot pot spot. I usually travel to Brooklyn to enjoy fine food I can’t get in Staten Island, I don’t make reviews but I also can’t make this bad experience go unwarranted. 1 Star for quality, service and effort, thank you.

The quality of the food is definitely better than AYCE hot pot places. The service is actually pretty good as well. However, they will make you sit at a small, cramped table for no reason.  Our party of five came in with a 6 pm reservation on a Friday night. The place is pretty small, but there was only about 1 or 2 other tables dining. They decided to seat us at a small, round table in the back (same space for a party of two, as we later saw). All of the food we ordered had to be placed on a separate tray/stand.  Unlike AYCE hot pot places and their self-serve sauce stations, Mister Hotpot brings the sauces to you, which was a nice change. However, they give you a dish with some concoction of soy sauce in them already, and it's A LOT of soy sauce. My suggestion to Mister Hotpot would be to just keep this on the side.  Aside from the small accommodations, everything else was pretty good. We decided to do two broths - their original soup base (comes with a serving of lettuce, enoki mushrooms, an egg, and some rice noodles) and the Szechuan spicy broth (which I personally don't like because it makes my tongue feel numb). Here's what we ordered:  Drunken Chicken - this is a mix of white and dark meat and is a pretty big portion. However, there is a big alcohol-y taste. The wine they use to marinate it doesn't completely cook off. Beef Combo (includes fatty beef, beef lung, and some other beef things) - the fatty beef, and one other cut of beef that was included was very good. I could do without the other beef parts. That being said, if you're not a fan of beef organs, you're better off just ordering the plates of beef itself, and not the combo. Pork Blood - good - nothing to complain about Fish Paste - this was my first experience at a restaurant having fish paste for hot pot and I really enjoyed it. They'll scoop it in to the pot for you, if you choose. Fish Ball - standard - pretty much what I expected. No different from the store bought ones. Cuttle Fish Ball - slightly better than store bought because I normally don't like cuttle fish balls, but I liked this one.  Overall, I had a good experience. I would recommend Mister Hotpot if you come with picky eaters and/or people with a small appetite. I'd come back again but probably with a group less than 5.
